00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:10.000
One of my favorite things that you can do really well thanks to the dplyr library that you led development of is piping.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:16.000
And so you can extremely easily have functions pass it.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:24.000
I mean, just like if people are familiar with Unix programming pipes there where you have output from one function goes the input to a next function.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:31.000
And prior to me discovering dplyr, which was probably around 2010.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.000
Does that make sense?

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:40.000
Prior to that, I would have so many variables in my workspace.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.000
It was just such a pain to keep them all straight.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:49.000
And you just end up in these weird situations where like should I be investing time thinking about the name of this intermediate variable?

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.000
Am I going to use this later?

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:58.000
Or should I just name it like intermediate variable 15 and have really ugly code?

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:05.000
So piping gets rid of all that where you can read the flows like a sentence.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:12.000
You're like, okay, this preprocessing step happens, then this next, and you can just see it so easily it makes it so elegant to read.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:22.000
Do you think we'll get to a point where and I have used some kinds of piping attempts in Python, but my experience of that has never been.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.000
And I guess it's been a few years since I've tried.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:25.000
Yeah.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:29.000
But it seems like it's never been as smooth or as easy as with R.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:32.000
And maybe that's related to what you were talking about earlier with data visualization.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:33.000
Yeah.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:41.000
So one, kind of like the native equivalent of piping in Python is like method chaining.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:45.000
You know, like if you're using pandas, you do something dot something.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
Yeah, pandas does it.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:48.000
Dot something.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:56.000
But the big difference between like method chaining and the pipe is in method chaining, like all of those methods have to come from the same class.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:00.000
They have to live in the same library, the same package.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:05.000
Whereas with piping, they can come from any package.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:25.000
And I think the thing that's really interesting about that is that that is meant like Python is tended to have like these fewer, bigger packages like pandas and scikit-learn, matplotlib, like kind of everything in order to work with method chaining, like everything has to be glommed into this one giant package.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:35.000
Where with R, you know, because you can combine things from different packages, like the equivalent of pandas is kind of like dplyr and tidyr and readr and a bunch of other things.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:46.000
It's way easier to add extensions to ggplot2 than matplotlib that work exactly the same way because you can just combine them with different pieces.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:34:01.000
So I think this is one of these like sort of interesting, like subtle differences in language design that leads to, you know, fairly big impacts on the user experience and kind of almost even how the community has to work together and form.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:02.000
Yeah, it makes perfect sense.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:05.000
And it's actually your explanation is so simple for how that's happened.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:12.000
And that had kind of escaped my attention as to why it works so well in R.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:20.000
When you were last on this podcast four years ago, you said that you wanted to marry the Python and R languages.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:28.000
Four years on, how do you assess the progress made in achieving this dream, especially through projects like Apache Arrow?

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:31.000
Yeah, I think we've come a long, a long way.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:43.000
And like Arrow has made a big difference in just being able to like seamlessly move data from one platform to another, you know, one programming language to another.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:51.000
I think the other, and then kind of coupled with that, I think the other technologies that's really, really interesting is DuckDB.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:57.000
You can, you know, you can use DuckDB from R, you can use it from Python and you don't have to have like a database file.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:35:00.000
You have like a directory full of parquet files.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:12.000
And it means that like, you know, people are using the same kinds of tools, just expressing them, you know, in the language that they feel most comfortable with.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:21.000
Another, you know, sort of a similar thing is like Keras and a lot of the machine learning toolkits in Python.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:25.000
Like the reason that they are fast is not because like Python is fast.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:33.000
It's because you express those high level ideas in Python and then they get compiled down to some low level machine code.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:43.000
And that's why packages like the Keras package for R, which is maintained by one of my colleagues at Posit, Tomasz Komarski, like it does the same thing.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:52.000
Like you express these ideas in R rather than Python, but then it gets compiled down to machine code using exactly the same toolkit.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:56.000
So I think that like we're just going to continue to see more and more of that.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.000
Like R is not fast.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.000
Python is not particularly fast.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:04.000
What is fast is like people really caring about stuff and Rust and C.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:08.000
And then you write a more user friendly interface on top of that.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:12.000
So the programming language is the data scientists use every day.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:13.000
Yeah.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:14.000
Yeah.

