00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:05.000
But another big innovation for our that has actually happened recently is R7.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:13.000
Which I heard about for the first time doing the research for this episode or reading search our researchers research.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:18.000
Yeah. Do you want to tell us about R7 and the problems that it's aimed to address?

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:22.000
So we actually renamed it to S7 relatively recently.

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:23.000
Oh, really?

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:25.000
It's called S7.

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:28.000
So it's called S7 because there are two.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:32.000
This is like a lot of historical minutiae.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:36.000
But R was like the language that came before R was called S.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:40.000
And S was the kind of introduced object-oriented programming.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.000
And S version 3 and S version 4.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:46.000
So in R there are two types of object-oriented programming.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.000
S3 and S4.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:51.000
Two chief types.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:48:02.000
And the kind of idea of S7 or R7 was to try and like take the add those two things together and get the best of both worlds.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:06.000
So S3 is like really just a very lightweight set of conventions.

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:10.000
Like it's not like object-oriented programming in any other language.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:12.000
Basically, it's very, very lightweight.

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:15.000
S4 kind of like swings too far in the other direction.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
It's like very formal.

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.000
There's a lot of kind of boilerplate.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:20.000
It's quite complicated.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.000
Things can go wrong in weird ways.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:26.000
So the idea of S7 was really to try and find like the sweet spot in between them.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:36.000
Like to take the nice features that S4 had, add them on top of S3 in a backward-compatible way so that we can hopefully switch.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:44.000
Hopefully, we're not just adding another object-oriented programming style to R, but we're actually supplanting S3 and S4 over time.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:49.000
Because everything you can do in those two, you can do in S7 and you can do it more easily.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:52.000
And there's better documentation and tooling and that kind of stuff.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:59.000
For our listeners who don't have a computer science background, what does it mean for a language to be object-oriented?

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:06.000
And that it can have these kinds of grades from lightweight, like you were describing with S3.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:08.000
Yeah, I don't know.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:11.000
I don't know.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:15.000
You have objects and you program with them.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:16.000
I don't know.

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:24.000
And it's especially weird in R because when you're using R, you're not really aware that you're using object-oriented programming.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:30.000
Unlike in Python, where I think you're much more aware that you have objects and you call methods on those objects.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:35.000
Object-oriented programming is much, much less important in R as a data scientist.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:39.000
I think you benefit from it because packages use it.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:46.000
So I think the main benefit to you as a data scientist is not that you're going to be writing S7 code.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:56.000
But the packages that you use are going to and they're going to be able to write code faster and more correctly from the get-go.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:50:01.000
So hopefully more of a general uplift of developer productivity in R.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:05.000
Probably not going to affect data scientists day-to-day that much.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:06.000
All right, cool.

