You created ggplot2, which is to this day the most popular data visualization library for R.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:50.000
It's had nearly 140 million downloads at the time of recording, which is crazy.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:57.000
And you have an associated book, ggplot2 elegant graphics for data analysis, which is super popular.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:05.000
And so my understanding from using ggplot2 now for over a decade, if I remember this correctly, you can tell me what I get wrong here or elaborate on a bit.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:10.000
But it's based on a grammar of graphics principle, which I guess was a book.

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:15.000
And that was like that didn't necessarily have anything to do with programming.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:19.000
It was just a way of expressing visual information.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:24.000
And you picked that up and you converted it into a programming framework.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:32.000
I mean, the grammar of graphics, the book by Lee Wilkinson really felt like it was a book like written for me because I read it.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:40.000
I was like, wow, this is how I want to be able to think about visualizations and describe visualizations with code.

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:50.000
And, you know, that's that's what I attempted to do, like turn the book into something that you could actually use for free with with open source software.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:57.000
If you go back and read the book, there's there's plenty of like deviations and places where maybe ggplot2 didn't capture the full spirit of it.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:02.000
But overall, I think it's a pretty a pretty high fidelity implementation.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:10.000
And just that idea of like pulling apart these pieces, like not thinking about this kind of like list of graphics, like a pie chart, a line chart, a bar chart.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:27.000
But thinking about these components that underlie the graphic, like the data and the scales and the geoms and the stats, like just a really, really powerful way to think about visualizations that allows you to create the thing that's like tailored specifically for your problem that maybe no one has ever created before.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:39.000
And so following on from this already very popular ggplot2 package, how do you envision the future of data communication, data publication, particularly with the development of tools like Quarto, which you mentioned earlier?

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:50.000
