00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:58.000
Yeah, I mean, Quarto at its heart is really a tool for communication, like particularly scientific and technical communication.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:06.000
Because what it allows you to do is integrate like your code and its results with your like thoughts about the results.

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:10.000
So you can write text and then integrate it with your results.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:22.000
And of course, like as opposed to like having a Word document where you may be copying and pasting plots, and with Quarto you end up with this document that is 100% reproducible.

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:30.000
As the data changes, you click a button, it reruns all the code, recombines everything together, and you have this like high fidelity document.

00:56:31.000 --> 00:56:40.000
And there's like a bunch of cool things about Quarto. Compared to its kind of predecessor R Markdown, Quarto works really well with Jupyter Notebooks as well.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:47.000
So if you've got a Jupyter Notebook, which is a fantastic tool for like you as a data scientist and your colleagues who are data scientists.

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:59.000
But if you're sharing that with other people, you might not want to share all the details. Quarto will help you turn that into like a polished, it could be a polished PowerPoint presentation, polished PDF, a polished website, a polished book.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:09.000
But something that's really aimed at not just showing like the mechanics, which of course you can show if you want, but like the thinking behind it, the explaining what's going on with the data.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:20.000
That's super cool. And I was a big user of R Markdown. I haven't used Quarto yet myself, and it sounds like I need to be, particularly for that element that you just described there of being able to hide things.

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:35.000
Like I have a number of times in my corporate life or in my commercial life created Jupyter Notebooks in situations where, for whatever reason, say a shiny tool wasn't the right thing.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:55.000
There was something about what I needed to be building where it made sense to me to create it in Python, in a Jupyter Notebook. And then I hand it off to somebody who doesn't program, and they have to see all kinds of things about the notebook that are probably confusing to see.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:59.000
Yeah. And so to be able to hide those things with Quarto sounds really cool.

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:09.000
