There's 161 cocktail recipes curated by yourself.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:52.000
You can browse by ingredients or browse by tags, so you can click through and say,

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:57.000
wow, I really like banana liqueur, and find all the cocktails with that in it.

01:06:57.000 --> 01:06:58.000
So that's a really fun resource.

01:06:58.000 --> 01:07:02.000
I'm sure there are some listeners out there that will be checking that out.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:04.000
I got that in the show notes for you.

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:07.000
So that's a fun thing to check out.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:13.000
Also, one of the first places where I was really kind of blown away— let's bring it

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:20.000
back to GNI again— is that that cocktail's website is powered by a YAML file that has

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:23.000
all the cocktails and the ingredients in.

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:25.000
And I was really impressed.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:30.000
When RStudio enabled Copilot integration, it just enabled it for every file, including

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:32.000
the YAML files.

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:38.000
So now I can just type in title and the name of the cocktail, and a good 75% of the time

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:43.000
it completes the ingredients using exactly the same YAML syntax that I use for every

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:44.000
other cocktail.

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:46.000
And I was just like, wow, that's pretty neat.

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:48.000
That's pretty cool.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:50.000
That is very cool.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:57.000
So my question for you is, given that you obviously have interests beyond just programming,

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:04.000
just work, how do you optimize your routine or your flows?

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:08.000
We talked about getting into a flow state earlier in this episode, so it sounds like

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:10.000
something that's important to you.

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:18.000
Also, we pulled out from a video that you made a long time ago— actually, it was just

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:27.000
a few months ago— on the PositPBC YouTube channel, you gave us a hint that key to your

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:31.000
routine is prioritizing creativity and productive work first.

01:08:31.000 --> 01:08:34.000
I don't know if you want to elaborate on that.

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:42.000
Yeah, I think one of the things we've tried to make part of the culture at RStudio and

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:47.000
now Posit is this idea of deep work, and that it's okay to carve out three or four hours

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:54.000
or more from your schedule to just be able to invest in some project that you need to

01:08:54.000 --> 01:08:56.000
have that level of focus on.

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:58.000
I still manage to do that.

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:05.000
I try and keep Tuesdays and Thursdays free from meetings so I can focus on programming

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:06.000
challenges.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:12.000
Recently, it feels like I've just had a lot more meetings and more manager stuff, which

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:18.000
I don't love.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:21.000
It's important.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:27.000
It's not something that amps me up, but I know it's important and I do it.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:32.000
That's something I think I'm really hoping to get back to more in the coming weeks, is

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:39.000
just carving out that time, finding some big technical problems to get my teeth into.

01:09:40.000 --> 01:09:45.000
One of the things I have been thinking about quite a lot and trying to learn more about

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:48.000
is R and production, or data science and production.

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:53.000
Just trying to understand what does that mean, really?

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:59.000
Then once I've turned solidly understood that, really thinking systematically, how can we

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:06.000
make that easier for folks using both of our open source products and with our pro products?

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:12.000
I'm excited to start digging into some of those technical challenges.

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:14.000
Yes, certainly.

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:18.000
That is another classic quip from Python developers, is that you don't use R in production, but

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:20.000
of course you can.

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:23.000
Lots to dig into there, I'm sure.

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:29.000
Beyond that, what else are you excited about in this fast-evolving data science field?

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:37.000
Are there particular challenges or paradigms that are up and coming that you're really

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:38.000
excited about?

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:44.000
I don't know if I'd say I'm excited about it, but interested in it is these ideas around

01:10:44.000 --> 01:10:46.000
data contracts.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:53.000
Now, like most folks, most or many data scientists are working hand-in-hand with data engineers

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:56.000
who are telling them that's where they get their data from.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:01.000
But often that data is not produced primarily for data scientists.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:04.000
It's produced for some other business purpose.

01:11:04.000 --> 01:11:11.000
Then the data engineers change that data in order to optimize that other business purpose.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:17.000
Then all of the data scientists' dashboards and models just break with confusing and bewildering

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:19.000
error messages.

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:26.000
That just seems like an interesting intersection of technical and people problems.

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:31.000
It definitely seems to be something a lot of companies are struggling with right now.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:37.000
I don't think I want to solve that, but I want someone to solve it so I can be like,

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:42.000
okay, this is a good framework for thinking about it, and then maybe I'll copy some of

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:45.000
the tooling in R to make that a bit easier.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:47.000
I think that's interesting.

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:54.000
Generally, I think just this whole, I'm not super invested in it, but just curious about

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:00.000
our aims and generative AI and how is that going to, particularly how is that going to

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:04.000
affect learning R for the first time, learning data science?

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:11.000
How can we, and teaching it too, because it fundamentally changes what questions you can

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:17.000
put on an assignment and expect what questions a student can answer without having to put

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:20.000
in any intellectual work of their own.

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:23.000
I'm very much always in the favor of lean into that.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:30.000
If now there's a question that a computer can answer, we need to find new questions.

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:32.000
I think that's just really, that's interesting.

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:37.000
It's not like, I don't know, I'm never, I don't know, I don't think I'm going to be

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:42.000
using my own models or training models or really understand the math behind them, but

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:48.000
just purely what are the, how does this change the way we think about teaching data science?

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:52.000
I think it's really interesting, and how can we build this into our tools?

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:56.000
What are the resources we should be thinking about?

01:12:56.000 --> 01:13:00.000
All that kind of stuff.

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:03.000
Yeah, interesting, exciting, and scary.

01:13:03.000 --> 01:13:10.000
I was a professor at the University of Illinois a couple of nights ago at the time of recording.

01:13:10.000 --> 01:13:13.000
Data Universe is a new conference that was just held for the first time in New York this

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:16.000
week at the time of recording.

01:13:16.000 --> 01:13:19.000
I met this University of Illinois professor at a dinner.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:24.000
He was sitting next to me, and he was doing some really cool things with Gen AI and education.

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:29.000
He had created a whole bunch of documents.

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:34.000
He was describing how there's this problem increasingly with getting corporations to

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:39.000
share real data for students to work with.

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:46.000
He created a fake company called Nile, which was supposed to be like Amazon, and created

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:54.000
dozens, generated dozens of business documents and data tables, and then had all of that

01:13:54.000 --> 01:14:01.000
built into a chat interface so that students could use that as a key stakeholder that they're

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:05.000
working with in the business and create data products for.

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:07.000
I thought that was cool.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:09.000
Yeah, so many possibilities.

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:12.000
It's going to take a while just to figure out how to use them effectively.

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:13.000
For sure.

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:15.000
All right, so that's the end of my questions.

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:17.000
I think we've got actually a crazy number.

01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:19.000
I'm going to have to curate them.

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:22.000
My apologies to listeners who asked so many questions.

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:27.000
I'm pretty sure a record number of questions for Hadley, which is cool.

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:32.000
It shows how much of an impact you have in the community in general, Hadley.

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:36.000
Yeah, lots of big name guests, but I've never seen anything like this.

01:14:36.000 --> 01:14:39.000
So I'm going to pick a few.

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:43.000
First of all, Austin Ogilvie, thank you for connecting me with Hadley.

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:47.000
He said that he's looking forward to this episode in one of his comments on LinkedIn.

01:14:48.000 --> 01:14:52.000
I should have mentioned it at the outset that it was thanks to Austin for connecting us,

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:53.000
that you are here.

01:14:53.000 --> 01:14:55.000
I really appreciate that.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:15:03.000
Me sheepishly making eye contact 10 years ago and not being willing to actually talk to you

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:09.000
at the Joyce Statistical meetings didn't cut the mustard.

01:15:09.000 --> 01:15:11.000
So here's one from Matias Baudino.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:13.000
Matias is a longtime listener.

01:15:13.000 --> 01:15:16.000
He's a BI analyst at a company called Brain Technology.

01:15:16.000 --> 01:15:23.000
And this question, it ties into a lot of the R and Python stuff we've been talking about here.

01:15:23.000 --> 01:15:26.000
He's wondering if there is a combination.

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:29.000
And you're probably, I don't know if this is something you would think about.

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:36.000
So is there a combination of Python libraries out there that could give you equivalent functionality

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:39.000
to the tidyverse, or is there nothing out there like that?

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:45.000
I will tell you that if such a thing existed, I would call it the pideyverse.

01:15:45.000 --> 01:15:52.000
But that is as far as I've gone.

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:57.000
I think there are two packages that are kind of close to the major pieces of the tidyverse,

01:15:57.000 --> 01:16:03.000
and that's plot nine for ggplot2 and suba that's very similar to dplyr.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:05.000
How do you spell that?

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:07.000
S-I-U-B-A.

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:11.000
Plot nine developed by Hassan, who I mentioned earlier,

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:17.000
and suba is developed by Michael Chow, who's also at Posit now.

01:16:17.000 --> 01:16:22.000
So I don't think we don't have any plans to try and make the pideyverse for Python.

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:25.000
I think Python is just a different environment.

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:27.000
It's much more diverse than R.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:33.000
It's not clear to me that having this kind of re-centralized cohesive set of packages would work.

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:37.000
But me and my team remain 100% focused on R,

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:44.000
so I hope I'm always happy to talk to people working on stuff in this area of Python

01:16:44.000 --> 01:16:49.000
and give my two cents, but not something that I'll be working on personally.

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:50.000
Nice.

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:54.000
And we had Doug McLean, who's the lead data scientist at Tesco back,

01:16:54.000 --> 01:16:58.000
also a longtime listener who's asked many questions of guests in the past.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:00.000
Thank you for all those, Doug.

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:07.000
He wanted to make sure that we talked about Shiny and deploying apps in R as well as in Python,

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:11.000
and he wanted to make sure that we talked about how much better R Markdown

01:17:11.000 --> 01:17:15.000
or now Porto is relative to Jupyter Notebooks.

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:16.000
So you get that.

01:17:16.000 --> 01:17:19.000
He wrote yuck next to Jupyter Notebooks.

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:24.000
I mean, Jupyter Notebooks are great as a tool for analysis.

01:17:24.000 --> 01:17:28.000
They're not great as a tool to share with decision makers in your organization.

01:17:28.000 --> 01:17:30.000
Quora now really fills that gap.

01:17:30.000 --> 01:17:36.000
You can have that Jupyter Notebook and then relatively easily turn it into a polished PDF

01:17:36.000 --> 01:17:39.000
or Word document or HTML file.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:43.000
It's really worth looking into if you use Jupyter.

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:48.000
Moving along from my LinkedIn post that you were coming up to, my Twitter post,

